        "heading": "Clinical Note",
        "section_value": "Chief Complaint\nRight knee pain\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports persistent right knee pain for the past three months, worsening with activity and stairs. He denies any specific injury. He describes the pain as a deep ache, with occasional sharp twinges. He has tried over-the-counter ibuprofen with minimal relief. He rates his pain as a 6/10 at rest and 8/10 with exertion.\nFindings\nThe patient demonstrates mild right knee effusion. Range of motion is limited by pain. Lachman's test is negative. McMurray's test is negative. Palpation reveals tenderness over the medial joint line.\nAssessment\nThe patient's symptoms and physical exam findings are consistent with medial meniscus injury.\nPlan\nOrder MRI of the right knee to evaluate for meniscal tears. Recommend physical therapy to improve range of motion and strengthen surrounding muscles. Advise the patient to avoid high-impact activities until further evaluation.",
